#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: we start w/ a ?: is a bx needed when u have suspicion for lupus nephritis?
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: we use the ISN/RPS classification over the WHO b/c it's thought to be more reproducible & ...
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: .. correlate with clinical prognosis.  though this is not proven
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal bx conference: reviewing ambiguous LMs in lupus, especially specimens that do'nt fit the classification
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: in ISN/RPS, proliferative & chronic lesions predict a poor prognosis; IV-S & IV-G r ~ prognosis
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: high activity in LN = cellular crescents, fibrinoid necrosis: predict bad prognosis
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference:role of REPEAT bx: predictive power of 2nd bx is not uniformly high
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: class switching occur more often if the 1st bx was a non-proliferative lesion
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: ISN/RPS doesn't account for IF/TA, renal vascular lesions, or any superimposed TMAs
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: don't bx LN-III or LN-IV pts who have active urinary sediment - it's likely 2 b a flare
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: mystery case 1: 26 M s/p KTx 2.5m ago, now w/azotemia + proteinuria
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: LM Jones shows back-to-back tubules w/o endothelitis but w/mesangial hypercellularity
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: correction -- GBM is THICK
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: EM shows no deposits in basement membrane, nl thickness (=375 nm +/- 45 nm), but FPE
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: correction - mesangial hyperexpansion, not hypercellularity, #1 dx diabetic nephropathy
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: in fact, the donor was an insulin-dependent diabetic

#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: mystery case 2: 65 m with renal failure & had a native bx
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: mesangial expansion on Jones LM, lots of IF (tubules not back to back), lots of vessel sclerosis
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: GBMs look thick on Jones LM (thick & black).  wrinkled tubules (suggest scarring)
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: EM shows thick GBM, no FPs, no deposits.  DDx: HTN, Diabetes. answer = both
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: clues to diabetic nephropathy = mesangial expansion (not hypercellularity) + thick GBM
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: case 3: 57 M with KTx bx, 1 episode of ACR previously
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: huge bowman's space, glomerular shrinkage, thick vessels, shrunken tubules
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: C4d neg, no ICs. wrinkled GBMs on Jones;
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: 45 M with proteinuria & hematuria
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: bx looks like obstruction but on U/S no HUN & tubules not dilated. dx- presumed obstruction
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: H/E shows mesangial hypercellularity with foam cells; sickled RBCs in glomerulus; huge glom
#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: dx = sickle cell anemia; EM shows FPE

#nephpearls 2/25: #Renal biopsy conference: Answer: amyloid because amyloidogenic LCs have different structural features than LCs in LCDD/CN

#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds 3/4/14: 2 factors play a role in diagnosis of IgA nephropathy = race & biopsy practices  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds 3/4/14: IgA nephropathy highly unlikely 2 b seen in AA patients; more likely in Asians  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: in Japan, there R established screening programs 4 pts w/proteinuria or micro hematuria  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: these screening practices result in more bx and higher diagnostic rates than in the US  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: in the US, bx of pt w/micro hematuria or mild proteinuria *not* routine unless high SCr  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: IgA nephropathy has 2 main presentations: asymptomatic urine abnormalities or hematuria...  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: ...usually hematuria occurs p infection, usually 1-2 days later   #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: in U of Chicago study 1980-94 higher freq of IgA nephro in Asian Am than in any other group  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: IgA nephropath also called Berger disease - died in 2011   #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: Berger was one of the first to describe mesangial deposits via EM (early 1960s)  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: Berger showed that the mesangial deposits that he saw on EM were IgA molecules  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: in the clinical presentation of IgA nephro, HTN is noted in 25% of cases & increases w/age  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: in brief, IgA produced in response to antigens in GI or respiratory tracts  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: these IgA antibodies are overprodced & deposit in the mesangium of the kidney  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: 2 subclasses of IgA in humans - type 1 and 2.  in IgA nephro, the most common subclass is 1  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: cannot make a mouse model for IgA nephro because mice don't make IgA-subclass 1  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: the mesangium is where the main pathology in IgA nephro occurs  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: the Lee scoring system: from Human Pathology 1982 p314-22  #meded #FOAMed
#nephpearls #Renal #grandrounds: Lee grade 1 = nl gloms, grade 2 = <50% gloms show mesang hypercellularity...  #meded #FOAMed

#renal #journalclub: background: adult Hb is HbA (97%). Remainder is HbA2 & HbF
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: Common Hb-opathies = HbS & HbC;  the difference is the AA that takes position 6 in the Hb protein
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: sickle trait is a heterozygous condition: HbS/HbA
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: we know that sickle trait can cause renal disease & hematuria
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: AA pts have lower Hb levels & require higher ESAs. Could this be due to the presence of sickle trait?
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: study design: 117 FMCNA pts w/Heterozygous Hb (incl sickle cell trait) & compared against normal AA pts
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: 4648 pts were in the control group, 671 in the heterozygous Hb group
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: within the heterozygous Hb group pts were differentiated by HbAC versus HbAS
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: almost 3 times HbAS pts as HbAC pts; all other baseline characteristics similar
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: all pts received in-center HD & had similar accesses, dialysis vintage, gender, age
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: heterozygous group received 7.9% higher dose than normal pts p < 0.02
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: big question: was multiple hypothesis testing correction employed in this study? Appears not as 12...
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: ..predictors in linear regression but statistical threshold 0.05; by Bonferroni should be 0.0041
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: author conclusions: HbAS common in AA dialysis patients, overall 13% higher ESA dose in trait groups..
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: .. To achieve same target Hb
#FOAMed #meded

#renal #journalclub: many ??s in audience about how the conclusions in this study can clinically help practitioners
